<section xml:id="algebra-principles" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Principles of Algebra</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Here we summarize the principles that define operations on the 
            set of real numbers. Methods of performing calculations, 
            simplifying algebraic expressions, and solving equations follow 
            from these principles.  
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <subsection>
        <title>Field Properties of the Real Numbers</title>
    <principle xml:id="principle-closure-reals">
        <title>Closure of Addition and Multiplication on the Set of Real Numbers</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are real numbers, then <m>a+b</m> and 
                <m>a\cdot b</m> are real numbers.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </principle>
    <principle xml:id="principle-commutative">
        <title>Commutative Laws</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are real numbers, then <m>a+b=b+a</m>
                and <m>a\cdot b=b\cdot a</m>.  
            </p>
        </statement>
    </principle>
    <principle xml:id="principle-associative">
        <title>Associative Laws</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                If <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are real numbers, 
                then <m>(a+b)+c=a+(b+c)</m>
                and <m>(a\cdot b)\cdot c=a\cdot (b\cdot c)</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </principle>
    <principle xml:id="principle-distributive">
        <title>The Distributive Law</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                If <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are real numbers, 
                then <m>c\cdot(a+b)=ca+cb</m>
                and <m>(a+b)\cdot c=ac+bc</m>.    
            </p>
            <p>
                Note that the distributive law also allows us to add fractions 
                with a common denominator;
                <me>
                    \frac{x}{d}+\frac{y}{d}=\frac{1}{d}\cdot x+\frac{1}{d}\cdot y
                    =\frac{1}{d}(x+y)=\frac{x+y}{d}.
                </me>
                In short, <m>\frac{x}{d}+\frac{y}{d}=\frac{x+y}{d}.</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </principle>
    <principle xml:id="principle-identity">
        <title>The Identity Properties</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                If <m>a</m> is an real number, then <m>a+0=a</m>, <m>0+a=a</m>,
                <m>a\cdot 1=a</m>, and <m>1\cdot a=a.</m> We call 0 the <term>additive identity</term>
                and 1 the <term>multiplicative identity</term>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </principle>
